{
  "text": "In Arabidopsis, two endogenous transcription factors move into neighboring cells: SHORTROOT (SHR) [CITATION_1] and LEAFY (LFY) [CITATION_2] . RNA of the GRAS-family transcription factor SHR is expressed in the stele of the root [CITATION_3] , but SHR protein is found in both the stele and the surrounding endodermis, which is missing in shr mutants. Further studies using transgenic misexpression confirmed that movement of SHR from the root stele to endodermis is required for endodermis development [CITATION_4] . RNA of the plant-specific transcription factor LFY is expressed in all three layers of young floral primordia, which are mis-specified as shoots in strong lfy mutants [CITATION_5] . Surprisingly, LFY RNA expression in the L1 of developing flowers is sufficient to fully rescue the lfy-mutant phenotype. In such transgenic plants, LFY protein, but not LFY RNA, is detected in all layers of the rescued flowers, indicating that LFY protein moves from the L1 into inner layers [CITATION_6] . By contrast, the transcription factor APETALA1 (AP1), which has similar in vivo functions as LFY but is structurally unrelated, behaves largely cell-autonomously [CITATION_7] .",
  "correct_citation": {
